h types are in hosts with similar SF rate and hence similar CC~SN\nrate, this can explain the mass difference between the SN~Ia and CC~SN hosts,\nand reinforce the finding that at least part of SNe~Ia should originate from\nvery old progenitors. Comparing the mean SFH of the eight least massive\ngalaxies to that of the massive SF SN~Ia hosts we find that the low-mass\ngalaxies formed their stars over more extended time than the massive SN~Ia\nhosts. We estimate that the low-mass galaxies should produce by a factor of 10\nless SNe~Ia, and a factor of 3 less CC~SNe than the high-mass group. Therefore\nthe ratio between the number of CC~SNe and SNe~Ia is expected to increase with\ndecreasing the galaxy mass. CC~SNe tend to explode at positions with younger\nstellar populations than the galaxy average, but the galaxy properties at\nSNe~Ia locations are one average the same as the global ones.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 4 Sep 2014 21:50:54 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 18 Sep 2014 00:48:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-02-20"}
